['\r\n                                Camille Pissarro is one of the leading Impressionist and Neo-Impressionist artists. His well known landscapes of his early career were significant influences of succeeding artists including Claude Monet and Paul Cezanne. In his later career, his focus and subject matter shifted to a more realistic depiction of peasant life, rather than the picturesque style that he had previously expressed. His work was praised and revered by many throughout his life, and will continue to be honored and celebrated to the present day.Artist’s alternative names: Camille Jacob Pissarro, Camille Pissaro.\n']

['\r\n                                Belgian artist, Rene Magritte, became known when he dramatically shifted his focus from his early career of Impressionist work to the more interesting and inspired Surrealist Movement. Similar to Marcel Duchamp, Magritte depicted mundane objects in his paintings and often gave them contradictory titles to provoke a feeling of irony and a sense of confusion from his audience. Magritte forced his viewers to question exactly what they were being exposed to. His work has inspired artists to subvert other art genres including theater, music and literature.\r\n                            ']

['\r\n                                Mark Rothko was born in Russia, but is considered to be an American Abstract Expressionist painter. Early in his career, Rothko was influenced by Surrealist artist Paul Klee and in later years by Piet Mondrian. Rothko established his own style over time, he began by using subject matter related to Greek and Roman mythology and would depict abstract figures. During what is considered his mature oeuvre, the artist began painting abstract canvases where color was the main protagonist, a technique known as Color Field painting. In his writings, Rothko noted that the abstract works were similar to those of a child yet he stressed the importance of color in the human developmental process.Artist’s alternative names: Mark Rothkowitz.\n']

['\r\n                                Jean-Michel Basquiat was an American artist who began as a graffiti artist in New York City in the late 1970s and evolved into a Neo-expressionist painter during the 1980s. At the young age of 23, Basquiat garnered a lot of fame and economic success, selling his paintings for hundreds of thousands of dollars. His close friendship and association with artist Andy Warhol helped assert his position within the art world. Unfortunately, during this successful period the artist was battling a heroin addiction and depression that was quickly growing more severe. Basquiat died at age 27 on August 12, 1988, of a heroin overdose.\r\n                            ']

['\r\n                                Celebrated artist Claude Monet is now the poster child of the French Impressionist style of painting and was the most prolific painter of the genre. Many of his most famous works are studies of light and color the artist would paint over the span of several days in different seasons, which is why there are so many similar paintings by the artist. Monet\'s paintings of his beloved water-lily gardens he tended to at his home in Giverny are of his most acclaimed masterpieces. One of these paintings, title "Le bassin aux nymphéas" (1919) sold at Christie\'s in 2008 for a record-breaking hammer-price of £36,500,000 ($71,892,376.34).Artist’s alternative names: Monet.\n']

['\r\n                                Henri Toulouse-Lautrec was a French Post Impressionist painter, printmaker, draftsman and illustrator. His work conveyed the feeling of the time in Paris, a colorful, theatrical and romantic, yet provocative period. Based mainly in Monmartre, an area in Paris that celebrated artistic expression, Toulouse-Lautrec, surrounded himself by a vibrant environment, which ultimately translated into his brightly colored, and active works of art. In addition to his surroundings, he was also influenced by Japanese woodprints and by Impressionist artists, Edgar Degas and Edouard Manet.Artist’s alternative names: Toulouse Lautrec.\n']

["\r\n                                Richard Diebenkorn was a well-known 20th century American painter whose early work was associated with Abstract Expressionism and the Bay Area Figurative Movement of the 1950s and 1960s. His later works (best known as the Ocean Park paintings) were instrumental to his achievement of worldwide acclaim. The Ocean Park series bridges his earlier abstract expressionist works with color field painting and lyrical abstraction. In 1991, he was awarded the National Medal of Arts.  Many works by the artist have been sold at auction, including 'Ocean Park # 48' sold at Christie's New York 'Post-War & Contemporary Evening Sale' in 2012 for $13,522,500. There have been numerous articles about Richard Diebenkorn, including 'The Seductive Lure of Abstraction' written by Terry Teachout for The Wall Street Journal in 2012.\r\n                            "]

["\r\n                                Max Ernst was a German painter, sculptor, graphic artist, poet and one of the primary pioneers of the Dada and Surrealist movements. Works by Pablo Picasso and Post-Impressionists such as Vincent Van Gogh and Paul Gauguin profoundly influenced Ernst's approach to art-making. After WWI, Ernst visited Paul Klee in Munich and studied paintings by Giorgio de Chirico, which left a deep impression on him. Constantly experimenting, in 1925 he invented a graphic art technique called frottage and another technique called 'grattage'. Ernst helped inspire the development of Abstract Expressionism in New York after he moved along with his friends, such as Marcel Duchamp and Marc Chagall, to the city during WWII.\r\n                            "]

['\r\n                                Influential Russian painter Wassily Kandinsky is credited with being the first purely abstract artist. He taught at the Bahaus School of Art and Architecture, where he continued cultivating his theories blending geometry and painting. Kandinsky lauded the influence of music in painting and deemed it as "the ultimate teacher." Kandinsky was one of the famed Die Blaue Vier (Blue Four) which included artists Lyonel Feininger, Alexej von Jawlensky, and Paul Klee.Artist’s alternative names: Vasilij Kandinskij, Vasily Kandinsky.\n']

["\r\n                                French artist Henri Matisse was a painter, sculptor, printer, and draftsman celebrated for his expressive use of color. The latter won him recognition as one of the preeminent masters of modern art and is world known for his iconic Fauvist style. He is credited with making significant advancements with regards to both painting and sculpture, with an oeuvre that spans over half a century. His work is recognized for his counterintuitive use of color as well as elongated and stylized representations of his subjects.  Many works by the artist have been sold at auction, including 'Nu de dos, 4 état (Back IV)' sold at Christie's New York 'Impressionist/Modern Evening Sale ' in 2010 for $48,802,500. There have been numerous articles about Henri Matisse, including 'They Met Over Coffee and Jackson Pollock' written by Warren Strugatch for New York Times Magazine in 2017.Artist’s alternative names: H. Matisse, Henri Emile Benoit Matisse, Henry Matisse, Matisse.\n"]

['\r\n                                19th-Century French painter Édouard Manet was a key figure in the transition from Realism to Impressionism. Manet\'s characteristic loose brush and flattened style translated well onto canvas, giving a fresh take on the contemporary subjects he favored. His painterly approach inspired an entire generation of future artists, and many of his masterworks, such as "Le Déjeuner sur l\'herbe" and "A Bar at the Folies-Bergère" are considered the archetypes of early modern art.Artist’s alternative names: Edouard Manet, Manet.\n']

['\r\n                                French artist Edgar Degas is often hailed as one of the founders of Impressionism. However, throughout his career the artist preferred to be called a realist. He is celebrated for his paintings, sculptures, prints and drawings, but is perhaps most famous for his works on the subject of dance - over half of the pieces in his oeuvre depict ballet dancers. The artist is also renown for his skilled portrayal of movement and the theatricality of the dance scenes as well as his portraits and nude renderings.Artist’s alternative names: Hilaire-Germain-Edgar Degas.\n']

["\r\n                                Georges Braque was a major 20th century French painter and sculptor known for developing Cubism alongside Pablo Picasso. Influenced by Paul Cézanne, Braque's paintings between 1908 and 1913 reflected his new interest in geometry and simultaneous perspective. In 1909 Braque began to work closely with Pablo Picasso, who had been developing a similar style of painting. Picasso celebrated animation, while Braque celebrated contemplation, and both artists produced paintings of monochromatic color and complex patterns of faceted form, now termed Analytic Cubism. By the time of his death in 1963, he was regarded as one of the elder statesmen of the School of Paris, and of modern art.Artist’s alternative names: G. Braque, George Braque.\n"]

['\r\n                                Having an introverted personality, Edward Hopper used his artwork to express what he could not verbally communicate. His work is a depiction of his reality and his understanding of modern America. Hopper used a variety of mediums and techniques, including watercolor, printmaking and etchings. His subject matter generally consisted of landscapes, both urban and rural, and the individuals who were involved with the environments he was portraying. He conveyed little movement, but was successful in capturing a candid, yet quiet moment in time through his work.\r\n                            ']

["\r\n                                Alexander Calder was typically known for his invention of the mobile sculptures and large sculptures. As one of the first artists to actively take his art to another level, Calder's reputation developed through his interesting abstract shapes and scientific materials such as pulleys, metals and cranks. He also created works in other medias such as paintings, lithographs, tapestry, kinetic toys, jewelry and domestic items. Calder is known for being a great influence on 1950's Paris-based artists that were exploring kinetics and op art.Artist’s alternative names: Sandy Calder.\n"]

['\r\n                                Swiss artist, Alberto Giacometti, had a distinctive style of painting, drawing and sculpture. Through his long, lean subjects and forms, and with his rough sketchwork and sculpting technique, Giacommetti established a look of his own. Although, his work was scruitinized and considered more expressionist than surrealist, Giacommetti played a major role in the development of  the Surrealist movement. His work "L\'Homme qui marche I" set a record at Sotheby\'s, London, where it was sold for £65 million (US$104.3 million).\r\n                            ']

['\r\n                                Donald Judd was an American artist associated with Minimalism, though he stridently disavowed this term. Nevertheless, he is generally considered the leading international exponent of Mimalism, and its most important theoretician through such seminal writings such as "Specific Objects" (1964). In his work, Judd sought autonomy and clarity for the constructed object and the space created by it, a concept also known as Phenomenology. His works ultimately achieve a rigorously democratic presentation without compositional hierarchy. His exploration created an outpouring of seemingly effervescent works that defied the term Minimalism.Artist’s alternative names: Donald Clarence Judd.\n']

['\r\n                                Known as one of the most significant members of the Viennese Secession, or Austrian Artists Union, Gustav Klimt set himself apart from other artistsof his group through his symbolic and erotic work. One of his most well known works of art is entitled, "The Kiss". With its mosaic-like technique and use of various mediums, including gold leaf, Klimt successfully captured the essence of a kiss as being an all encompassing experience. Klimt\'s "Portrait of Adele Bloch Bauer II" is also notoriously known for a high profile international case that involved Bloch Bauer\'s niece Maria Altmann. Altmann managed to reclaim her aunt\'s portrait, which was looted from the Nazis during WWII and reappeared in the Austrian State Gallery after the war ended. The painting, considered the "Mona Lisa of Vienna", was sold at Christie\'s in New York for $88 million becoming the fourth highest-priced artwork sold at auction.Artist’s alternative names: Gustav Klint.\n']

['\r\n                                Philip Guston was a New York School painter and printmaker. Abandoning so-called "pure abstraction" in favor of more cartoonish renderings of personal symbols and objects, Guston helped lead a transition from Abstract Expressionism to Neo-Expressionism in painting in the late 1960s. Italian painter Giorgio de Chirico was a powerful influence whom Guston referenced throughout his career. Guston is best known for his late existential and lugubrious paintings which became popular at the time of his death.\r\n                            ']

['\r\n                                French artist, Paul Cezanne, is one of the most influential painters of the twentieth century. Cezanne was deeply involved in the development of art from the Post Impressionist style to the Cubist movement. His knowledge and understanding of composition, color, and forms were major elements that attribute his success as a master artist. He influenced the work of later artists, such as Pablo Picasso and Georges Braque.Artist’s alternative names: Cézanne, Paul Cezanne.\n']

["\r\n                                Tom Wesselmann was an American artist associated with the Pop Art movement who worked in painting, collage and sculpture. Wesselmann never liked his inclusion in American Pop Art, pointing out how he made an aesthetic use of everyday objects and not a criticism of them as consumer objects. Wesselmann's series Great American Nude (begun 1961) brought him to the attention of the art world and today he is considered one of the most influential American artists of the twentieth century.\r\n                            "]

["\r\n                                Henry Moore was born in Yorkshire in 1898, and enrolled as the first sculpture student at Leeds School of Art after serving during World War I.  Moore received a scholarship to pursue studies at the Royal College of Art in London. While there he spent ample time at the British Museum studying their ethnographic collections, which strongly informed his later monumental figurative works.  He lived in Paris, enrolling in classes that periodically met at the Louvre, and encountered an Aztec sculpture at the Musée d'Ethnographie that would be a crucial influence on his early work.  This sculpture encouraged his inclination to create direct carved, single figures focused on their mass and form. He made his first prints in 1931 and altogether made something over 700 prints during his career.  From the late 1960s printmaking became an increasingly important part of Moore’s artistic output and as with his sculpture and drawings two abiding themes were reclining female forms and mother and child. Moore’s artwork has been exhibited extensively at notable venues such as the Museum of Modern Art, Metropolitan Museum of Art, New York, Royal Academy of Arts, London, Shanghai Art Museum, National Gallery of Art, Washington DC, Tate Britain, London, Kremlin Museum, Moscow and many other institutions around the world.Artist’s alternative names: Henry Spencer Moore, Moore.\n"]

['\r\n                                20th century American artist Roy Lichtenstein rose to prominence with his iconic works inspired by comic strips. Lichtenstein is considered a leading figure of the Pop Art movement, along with Andy Warhol, Jasper Johns, and others. The influence of comics and advertising are clearly portrayed in his works. His aforementioned "comic strip" style works were often parodies of contemporary social themes.\r\n                            ']

One of the painting techniques that Bonnard was known for was his ability to paint from a photograph, a drawing or notes he recorded for himself. His subjects were rarely painted in real life. This allowed him to experiment with his use of color and light.\r\n                            ']

["\r\n                                Lucian Freud was a German-born British painter. Known chiefly for his thickly impastoed portrait and figure paintings, he was widely considered the pre-eminent British artist of his time. Freud's early paintings are often associated with German Expressionism and Surrealism. From the 1950s, he began to work in portraiture, often nudes to the almost complete exclusion of everything else. He developed a free style, with an intense concentration on texture and color of flesh by using thicker paint and impasto. His works are noted for their psychological penetration, and for their often discomorting examination of the relationship between artist and model.Artist’s alternative names: Lucien Freud.\n"]

['\r\n                                Leonardo da Vinci is one of the most well known artists of all time. Known as the creator of popular works such as \'Mona Lisa\' and \'The Last Supper\', Da Vinci successfully established himself through the medium of painting. However, the artist was also mastered other interests including sculpture, mathematics, music, architecture, geology and science. Such wide range of interests and abilities deemed him as a "Renaissance man". In painting, his approach consisted of a precise and scientific composition as well as a complete understanding of the use of color, line and form. His work was celebrated throughout his life with commissions by royalty, and continue to be revered to the present day.\r\n                            ']

['\r\n                                Max Beckmann was a German painter, draftsman, printmaker, sculptor, and writer. Although he is classified as an Expressionist artist, he rejected both the term and the movement and in the 1920s. Beckman instead associated with the New Objectivity (Neue Sachlichkeit) group, which was an outgrowth of Expressionism that opposed its introverted emotionalism. He is known for the self-portraits painted throughout his life, their number and intensity are rivaled only by Rembrandt and Picasso. Unlike several of his avant-garde contemporaries, Beckmann rejected non-representational painting; instead, he took up and advanced the tradition of figurative painting.\r\n                            ']

['\r\n                                Edwin Parker "Cy" Twombly, Jr. was an American artist well known for his large-scale, freely scribbled, calligraphic-style graffiti paintings, on solid fields of mostly gray, tan, or off-white colors. Twombly\'s paintings blur the line between drawing and painting; he is said to have influenced younger artists such as Anselm Kiefer, Francesco Clemente, and Julian Schnabel. In 1990 a Christie\'s auction set a record for Twombly with his 1971 untitled blackboard painting fetching $5.5 million. In 2011, a Twombly work from 1967, "Untitled", sold for $15.2 million at Christie\'s in New York.  Many works by the artist have been sold at auction, including \'UNTITLED (NEW YORK CITY)\' sold at Sotheby\'s New York \'Contemporary Art Evening Auction\' in 2015 for $70,530,000. There have been numerous articles about Cy Twombly, including \'Cy Twombly\'s Delicate \'Dryprints\'\' written by Anna Jenkinson for The Wall Street Journal in 2012.\r\n                            ']

['\r\n                                Influential Italian painter and sculptor Lucio Fontana is celebrated for founding Spatialism and for his ties to Arte Povera. He executed his unique paintings by use of bright colors, mixed media, and slash cuts to the canvas. A rare, large crimson work with a single slash - his infamous "Teresita"- fetched a record £6.7m ($11.6m) at Christie’s London in 2008. Fontana\'s widely acclaimed oval canvases continue to fare well at auction, such as his 1964 work "La fine di Dio," which sold for $29,173,000 at auction at Christie\'s London in November of 2015.  Many works by the artist have been sold at auction, including \'Concetto spaziale, La fine di Dio\' sold at Christie\'s New York \'Post-War & Contemporary Evening Sale\' in 2015 for $29,173,000. There have been numerous articles about Lucio Fontana, including \'Art review: \'Suprasensorial: Experiments in Light, Color and Space\' at MOCA\' written by Christopher Knight for Los Angeles Times in 2010.\r\n                            ']

['\r\n                                French artist, Paul Gauguin, was one of the most significant Post-Impressionist painters of the 19th century. His work suggested a primitive style and evidence of his involvement with the Symbolist Movement. His desire to explore "the exotic" led him to several trips to the island Tahiti. The island\'s surroundings were an important influence in subject matter and technique, and is considered to have played a major role in the development of modern art. His work influenced artists such as Pablo Picasso and Henri Matisse, and has been exhibited worldwide.\r\n                            ']

["\r\n                                Marc Chagall was a Belorussian-French artist associated with several major artistic styles and one of the most successful artists of the twentieth century. He was an early modernist, and created works in virtually every artistic medium, including painting, book illustrations, stained glass, stage sets, ceramic, tapestries and fine art prints. Heavily influenced by Fauvism and Cubism, Chagall's paintings are known for their lose brushwork and use of a bright and varied color palette. Chagall's Jewish identity became a key subject matter in his artwork.\r\n                            "]

['\r\n                                Joan Miró was a painter, printmaker, sculptor, and ceramicist from the Catalan region in Spain. His work has earned international acclaim and has been deemed as Surrealist although he conducted his own exploration of this style. His interests ranged from automatic drawing to expressionism, Lyrical Abstraction, and Color Field painting. Miró is recognized for his signature biomorphic forms, semi-abstracted figures and a limited color palette.Artist’s alternative names: Joan Miro, Miro, Miró.\n']

['\r\n                                Giorgio de Chirico was a pre-Surrealist and then Surrealist Italian painter who founded the scuola metafisica art movement. De Chirico is best known for his his metaphysical period paintings, produced between 1909 and 1919, memorable for the haunted, brooding moods evoked by their images. In 1939, he adopted a neo-Baroque style influenced by Rubens, but these later paintings never received the same critical praise as did those from his metaphysical period. De Chirico strongly influenced the Surrealist movement, as well as modern photographer Duane Michals, Italian film director Michelangelo Antonioni, writers including John Ashbery and Sylvia Plath, and even the critically acclaimed video game Ico.\r\n                            ']

['\r\n                                Hugely influential painter Jackson Pollock was a prominent figure in the abstract expressionist movement, which became popular in the late 1940\'s and 1950\'s. While known for being mostly reclusive with a volatile personality, Pollock gained considerable notoriety and fame during his lifetime, and his works are still widely celebrated today, most notably his "drip" paintings he created at the height of his career. Since his death in 1956, several major art institutions have held large-scale retrospectives featuring his work.Artist’s alternative names: jackson pollack, Pollock.\n']

["\r\n                                Joan Mitchell was an essential member of the American Abstract expressionist movement, though her career mainly occurred in France. She was one of her era's few female painters to gain critical and public acclaim. Among others, she was initially influenced by Van Gogh, Cézanne and Kandinsky, and later by Franz Kline and Willem de Kooning. The subject matter of her expansive paintings, often covering two panels, was mainly influenced by landscape and used bright colors. However, her works between 1960-64 depict sombre tones and express something primordial. Today the Joan Mitchell Foundation awards grants and stipends to painters, sculptors, and artist collectives.  Many works by the artist have been sold at auction, including 'Untitled' sold at Christie's New York 'Post-War & Contemporary Evening Sale' in 2014 for $11,925,000. There have been numerous articles about Joan Mitchell, including 'New York Art Gallery Review: Nancy Rubins, Jerry Kearns and Joan Mitchell' written by Peter Plagens for The Wall Street Journal in 2014.\r\n                            "]

['\r\n                                Celebrated artist Pablo Picasso was a painter, draughtsman, and sculptor who lived most of his life in France. He is widely known for co-founding the Cubist movement and his revolutionary artistic accomplishments make him one of the best-known and influential figures in twentieth century art. Picasso\'s advancements in Cubism influenced countless artists all over the world for many years after he stopped using this style in his own work. The artist\'s masterpiece "Demoiselles d\'Avignon" is considered as the most important work of the modern period, it is currently exhibited at the Museum of Modern Art in New York.Artist’s alternative names: Pablo Ruiz y Picasso, Picaso, Picasso.\n']

['\r\n                                Andy Warhol (1928-1987) could be the most influential artist of the 20th century. The Metropolitan Museum of Art in New York recently contributed to the argument for this point of view with their 2012 exhibition Regarding Warhol: Sixty Artists, Fifty Years, which juxtaposed Warhol’s work with work by artists from Cindy Sherman to Christopher Wool that have followed in his footsteps in style or method. In the early 60s Warhol helped usher in an era of Pop art using culturally iconic images in his work from the popular media, like Campbell’s soup cans and celebrity figures including Marilyn, Elvis and Jackie O. But his élan for experimentation and innovation did not end there. He problematized authorship making unique works from silkscreens in series, and called his studio The Factory where he allowed assistants to make art in his stead. His practice was truly multimedia before anyone really took anything but his paintings seriously. As early as 1963 he began making films, and from 1965-67 he managed the band The Velvet Underground. In 1968 he announced an end to his painting career and founded Interview Magazine instead. He of course did return to painting in 1972 with his famous Mao series and continued to introduce new ideas with bodies of work as diverse as the abstract leaning Shadow paintings and the last series he completed before his death based on Leonardo da Vinci’s The Last Supper.\r\n                            ']

['\r\n                                Italian artist, Amedeo Modigliani, began his artistic career studying the styles of Renaissance artists. As his technique developed the popularity of Renaissance themes shifted to landscapes, but he refused to succumb to the pressure of his fellow artists gravitating to the new popular subject. Modigliani moved to Paris and was exposed to a new artistic lifestyle upon his arrival. He became very involved in the bohemian, dramatic and romantic surroundings of the city. As a result of his inspired environment Modigliani discovered his passion among figurative paintings more specifically, nudes. Modigliani began painting African mask-like faces, and elongated features which established the reputation for his own personal style among fellow artists.Artist’s alternative names: Amadeo Modigliani, Modigliani.\n']

['\r\n                                Andrew Wyeth was a visual artist, primarily a realist painter, working in a regionalist style. He was one of the best-known U.S. artists of the middle 20th century. In 1963 he was the first painter to receive the Presidential Medal of Freedom. Wyeth\'s favorite subjects were the land and people around him, both in his hometown and his summer home. One of the most well-known images in 20th-century American art is his painting "Christina\'s World", painted at his Maine summer home, currently in MoMA\'s collection. Yet Wyeth\'s art has long been controversial, and critics, curators and historians have offered conflicting views about the importance of his work.Artist’s alternative names: Andrew Newell Wyeth.\n']

['\r\n                                Fernand Léger was a French painter, sculptor, and filmmaker. Initially trained as an architect, his early works are known for showcasing the lasting influence of Cubism. Leger\'s early works are often referred to as Salon Cubism. The "mechanical" works Léger painted in the 1920s are typical of postwar art, and link him to the tradition of French figurative painting represented by Poussin and Corot. His bold and simplified treatment of modern subject matter led him to be regarded as a forerunner of Pop Art.\r\n                            ']

['\r\n                                Although educated and trained in architecture, Ernst Kirchner, became interested in fine arts through his elective courses in Germany. As a result of his art classes, Kirchner collaborated with two other architects and founded the group called Die Brücke, "The Bridge". The group was created in order to move artistic style from an old method of expression to a more contemporary form of art. In doing this, Kirchner established and developed his personal style through his colorful and less realistic depiction of human forms, with an emphasis on the expression and personality of his subjects. He was involved in one of the first modern art and his work has sold for a record breaking $38 million in 2006.Artist’s alternative names: kirshner.\n']

The theme in his paintings were mainly candid moments or intimate settings, captured through his technique that created a smooth contrast from primary subject to its environment. His work was heavily influenced by other major artists including: Edgar Degas, Édouard Manet and Eugène Delacroix.Artist’s alternative names: Auguste Renoir, Renoir.\n']
